    <fr:title text="What is a Vernacular Language?">What is a Vernacular Language?</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Problem</fr:taxon>
    <fr:authors />
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We have a precise definition of the <fr:link type="local" href="kernel.xml" addr="kernel" title="Kernel Languages">kernel</fr:link>, but not exactly one for the <fr:link type="local" href="vernacular.xml" addr="vernacular" title="Vernacular Languages">vernacular</fr:link>. The vernacular is a <fr:em>metalanguage</fr:em> in that it can inspect kernel propositions -- the syntax of the vernacular is the content of the kernel. Can we make the definition more precise?</fr:p>
    <fr:p>The motivation for this is to formalize what a vernacular <fr:em>is</fr:em> so that we can develop abstractions over them, for the purposes of <fr:link type="local" href="proof-assistant-explosion.xml" addr="proof-assistant-explosion" title="Constructing Proof Assistants">making proof assistant construction easier</fr:link>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
